SubTopics: Use context as a clue to the meaning of a word or a phrase.
Content: In paragraph 3, what is the meaning of the word “passive” as it is used in the last sentence?

A.Choice: unimpressed

B.Choice: unnatural

C.Choice: unconcerned

D.Choice: unappreciative

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which statement BEST describes the central idea of paragraphs 2–5?

A.Choice: The author is considering sacrificing one of his favorite things for financial gain.

B.Choice: The author recognizes that changing his habits would be beneficial but is still reluctant to change.

C.Choice: The author is aware that some habits are bad for you but thinks the risks are worth it to enjoy life.

D.Choice: The author realizes that his approach to decision-making is overly complicated and should be simplified.

SubTopics: Demonstrate understanding of figurative language, word relationships, and nuances in word meanings in grades 9-10 reading and content; interpret figures of speech in context and analyze their role in a text; analyze nuances in the meaning of words with similar denotations.
Content: What TWO things is the author implying when he uses the figurative language “thorny issue” in paragraph 16 of the passage?

A.Choice: Experimentation could be complicated and create unintended consequences.

B.Choice: Experimentation may not happen because of prolonged discussions.

C.Choice: Experimentation may not be worth the risks associated.

D.Choice: Experimentation could be restricted because of current laws.

E.Choice: Experimentation with high stakes consequences may be met with public reluctance.

SubTopics: Analyze how an author presents and develops key ideas and events to impact meaning.
Content: The following item has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Which statement BEST summarizes the author's main point regarding one of the reasons people are so resistant to change?

A.Choice: People do not want to seem unconfident to those around them.

B.Choice: People do not want to seem inflexible to those around them.

C.Choice: When making changes, a person may actually not be aware of alternatives.

D.Choice: When making changes, a person may end up not gaining any advantage.

Content: Which sentence in the passage does the author use to develop the correct answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “And when I think of all the lunch places near my workplace, I realize that I keep going to the same places again and again.” (paragraph 11)

B.Choice: “I might not like what I get and must forgo something I already enjoy.” (paragraph 12)

C.Choice: “That cost is immediate, while any benefits ─ even if they are large ─ will be enjoyed in a future that feels abstract and distant.” (paragraph 12)

D.Choice: “I am unduly certain in my guesses of what the alternatives will be like, even though I haven't tried them.” (paragraph 13)

SubTopics: Analyze what a text says explicitly and draw inferences; cite the strongest, most compelling textual evidence to support conclusions.
Content: Read these sentences from paragraph 10.

:ibox:The closings imposed by the strike forced experimentation with alternate routes, yielding valuable results. And if the strike had been longer, even more improvements would probably have been discovered.
Which TWO inferences is the author making as underlying assumptions for these statements?

A.Choice: People would have eventually spoken to one another and shared ideas for other forms of transportation.

B.Choice: People would be more willing to experiment since their original habit had already been interrupted.

C.Choice: People did not think deeply about their choices of alternative routes because they were unhappy about the inconvenience.

D.Choice: People would have eventually calculated how little time the alternative routes were really saving, so they would only make a temporary change.

E.Choice: People did not believe changes in routes were necessary because the interruption would be short-lived.

SubTopics: Analyze how an author presents and develops key ideas and events to impact meaning.
Content: How does the author develop the idea that people have a difficult time seeing the benefits of making a change?

A.Choice: He talks about how long it would take to see any monetary difference in his expenses if he gave up Diet Coke.

B.Choice: He explains that the sacrifice one makes is felt immediately but envisioning the rewards is a more abstract concept.

C.Choice: He uses an example of a company hiring an individual and then having to wait to see if that individual performs to preconceived expectations.

D.Choice: He uses an example of commuters on the London Underground being inconvenienced by the strike, without mentioning how the strike helped the workers who run the system.

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: The following item has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Which statement BEST describes the central idea of paragraphs 15–17?

A.Choice: The ways that businesses and the government are structured discourage experimentation.

B.Choice: One must be self-aware to understand that he or she is likely unable to always make fair decisions.

C.Choice: Businesses and the government are often overly optimistic about the benefits of making different choices.

D.Choice: An unwillingness to experiment in one's personal life often extends to professional settings.

Content: Select the detail from paragraphs 15–17 that BEST helps support the correct answer to Part A.

A.Choice: “Executives and policymakers fail to experiment in their jobs, ...” (paragraph 15)

B.Choice: “... in the sense of playing with people's lives.” (paragraph 16)

C.Choice: “... whereas the current policy may actually be a wobbly structure held together by overconfidence, ...” (paragraph 16)

D.Choice: “... there is simply no way of knowing without trying something different.” (paragraph 17)

SubTopics: Analyze how an author's ideas or claims are developed and refined by particular sentences, paragraphs, or larger portions of a text.
Content: Which TWO statements MOST LIKELY explain why the author discusses his intake of Diet Coke before he discusses the ideas in paragraphs 5 and 6?

A.Choice: to imply that he will be asking the reader to make a lifestyle change that will provide big rewards

B.Choice: to provide the reader with an easily understood example of a difficult concept

C.Choice: to establish for the reader that the size of risks he will be discussing range greatly in severity

D.Choice: to establish himself with the reader as having insight on the subject based on his personal experience

E.Choice: to imply that the reader will have to make choices that could affect future happiness

SubTopics: Analyze what a text says explicitly and draw inferences; cite the strongest, most compelling textual evidence to support conclusions.
Content: Which inference about the author is BEST supported by the passage as a whole?

A.Choice: He will eventually start buying generic medications.

B.Choice: He will eventually decide to give up his habit of drinking Diet Coke.

C.Choice: Because of his professional training, he tends to think about how changing his personal habits would result in saving money.

D.Choice: Because of his professional training, he has spent much time researching the impact of lack of changes made by the government.

SubTopics: Use context as a clue to the meaning of a word or a phrase.
Content: What does the phrase “quick staccato” mean as it is used in paragraph 7?

A.Choice: clumsy or awkward response

B.Choice: shortened or abbreviated manner

C.Choice: natural or ordinary reaction

D.Choice: practiced or customary fashion

SubTopics: Analyze what a text says explicitly and draw inferences; cite the strongest, most compelling textual evidence to support conclusions.
Content: Which sentence BEST describes the interaction between Mrs. Hall and the stranger in paragraph 2?

A.Choice: Mrs. Hall is intent on impressing her unexpected customer.

B.Choice: The stranger is hesitant about taking a room at the inn.

C.Choice: The stranger complains about the effects of being out in the cold.

D.Choice: Mrs. Hall takes pity on a man driven into her inn by the storm.

SubTopics: Use context as a clue to the meaning of a word or a phrase.
Content: What does the word “stateliness” mean as it is used in paragraph 9?

A.Choice: formality

B.Choice: expectancy

C.Choice: attention

D.Choice: hesitation

SubTopics: Analyze what a text says explicitly and draw inferences; cite the strongest, most compelling textual evidence to support conclusions.
Content: Read this excerpt from paragraph 10.

:ibox:She rapped down the mustard pot on the table, and then she noticed the overcoat and hat had been taken off and put over a chair in front of the fire. A pair of wet boots threatened rust to her steel fender. She went to these things resolutely. “I suppose I may have them to dry now,” she said in a voice that brooked no denial.
What does this excerpt reveal about Mrs. Hall?

A.Choice: She is becoming irritated by the stranger's behavior.

B.Choice: She is particular about the guests she allows at the inn.

C.Choice: She is worried that the stranger thinks poorly about her.

D.Choice: She is determined to learn more about the stranger.

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: How does the stranger's interaction with Mrs. Hall help develop the story?

A.Choice: His polite but reserved behavior conceals his true intentions.

B.Choice: His refusal to remove his hat and coat creates a hostile mood.

C.Choice: His lack of conversation makes him appear secretive and suspicious.

D.Choice: His direct manner of speaking signals that he finds her annoying.

SubTopics: Use context as a clue to the meaning of a word or a phrase.
Content: Read this sentence from paragraph 9.
:ibox:And while she herself finished mixing the mustard, she gave Millie a few verbal stabs for excessive slowness.
What do the words “verbal stabs” mean as used in this sentence?

A.Choice: excuses

B.Choice: reminders

C.Choice: insults

D.Choice: suggestions

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which statement expresses a central idea of the passage?

A.Choice: Mrs. Hall worries that her new guest will create a mess in the inn.

B.Choice: The stranger who comes to the Coach and Horses Inn has something to hide.

C.Choice: The stranger is angered by Mrs. Hall's attempts to make him comfortable.

D.Choice: Mrs. Hall is embarrassed by the poor condition of the Coach and Horses Inn.

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: How does the setting of this story help shape the plot?

A.Choice: The wintry weather makes it easy for the stranger to hide his appearance.

B.Choice: The confined area of the inn makes it difficult for the stranger to avoid people.

C.Choice: The safety of his room at the inn allows the stranger to be relaxed and open.

D.Choice: The turmoil created when the stranger arrives distracts from his behavior.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: The following item has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What is a central idea developed throughout the passage?

A.Choice: Mrs. Hall's business is in financial trouble and may soon have to close.

B.Choice: The stranger who arrives at the Coat and Horses Inn is being pursued.

C.Choice: Mrs. Hall's outward behavior conceals her true feelings about her guest.

D.Choice: The new guest at the Coat and Horses Inn would prefer to be left alone.

Content: Which phrase from the passage supports the correct answer in Part A?

A.Choice: “A guest to stop at Iping in the winter-time was an unheard-of piece of luck, ...” (paragraph 2)

B.Choice: “He made no answer and had turned his face away from her ...” (paragraph 7)

C.Choice: “He held a white cloth over the lower part of his face, ...” (paragraph 13)

D.Choice: “Her nerves began to recover from the shock ...” (paragraph 14)

SubTopics: Analyze what a text says explicitly and draw inferences; cite the strongest, most compelling textual evidence to support conclusions.
Content: Read the final paragraph of the passage.
:ibox:“Thank you,” he said drily, glancing from her to the door and then at her again.
What message is the stranger conveying to Mrs. Hall in this paragraph?

A.Choice: He wants Mrs. Hall to treat him with courtesy.

B.Choice: He wants Mrs. Hall to leave the room.

C.Choice: He wants Mrs. Hall to stop speaking firmly to him.

D.Choice: He wants Mrs. Hall to be patient with his strange ways.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which statement is the BEST summary of this passage?

A.Choice: After a guest at the Coach and Horses Inn arrives cold and wet, Mrs. Hall offers him a warm room and a meal.

B.Choice: Forced in to the Coach and Horses Inn by a bad storm, a stranger refuses the owner's offer to dry his coat.

C.Choice: The unusual behavior of a new guest at the Coach and Horses Inn surprises the owner as she tries to serve him.

D.Choice: A guest at the Coach and Horses Inn becomes irritated when the owner barges into his room to bring him lunch.

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: How does Mrs. Hall change from the beginning to the end of this excerpt?

A.Choice: She is initially upset about the mess the stranger makes but becomes sympathetic after seeing his bandaged head.

B.Choice: She is happy when the unexpected guest arrives at the hotel but is stunned by his appearance when he removes his hat.

C.Choice: She is anxious when the stranger arrives at the inn but compassionate when she learns more about him.

D.Choice: She is briefly worried that her new guest will not be satisfied with the inn but is reassured by his decision to stay.

SubTopics: Determine the meaning of words and phrases as they are used in a text, including figurative and connotative meanings; analyze the cumulative impact of specific word choices on meaning and tone, such as how language evokes a sense of time and place, and how it communicates an informal or formal tone.
Content: The following item has TWO parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What tone is established by the author of the passage?

A.Choice: mysterious

B.Choice: impatient

C.Choice: gloomy

D.Choice: tragic

Content: Which TWO details from the passage BEST help create the tone?

A.Choice: “the burden he carried” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “took up his quarters” (paragraph 1)

C.Choice: “standing with his back to her” (paragraph 2)

D.Choice: “a sound repeated at regular intervals” (paragraph 9)

E.Choice: “a glimpse of a white object disappearing” (paragraph 10)
